title: Apply for parole if you're a young offender

heading_context: Apply for parole if you're a young offender
chunks.html_content:
You might be able to get parole as a young offender if you’re:

  • a young adult (18 to 21)
  • a juvenile (under 18)

Parole means you can leave prison or be released from custody before the end of your sentence, but you’ll be kept under supervision.

You may have to apply for parole yourself or the government may apply for you depending on what kind of sentence you’re serving.

You’ll need a solicitor to help you get parole. Ask a member of the prison staff for help getting one if you don’t already have a solicitor. You might be able to get legal aid to help pay for this.

heading_context: Apply for parole if you're a young offender
chunks.html_content: There are different rules for adults. There are also different rules in Scotland and rules in Northern Ireland.

heading_context: Apply for parole if you're a young offender
When you can apply
chunks.html_content:
You can apply for parole if you’re serving a fixed-term sentence (where you’re in custody for at least 4 years) and you’re not eligible for being released automatically halfway through your sentence.

You’ll be able to apply 6 months before your ‘tariff’ runs out, which is usually halfway through your sentence. Your tariff is the minimum length of time you were ordered to stay in prison.

heading_context: Apply for parole if you're a young offender
When the government will apply for you
chunks.html_content:
The government will apply for parole for you if you’re serving a life sentence. You’ll have to serve your tariff before you can be considered for parole.

You’ll be contacted:

  • 3 years before your tariff runs out if you’re serving a sentence of 4 years or more
  • at least 6 months before your tariff runs out if you’re serving a shorter sentence

heading_context: Apply for parole if you're a young offender
Get help where you’re being held in custody
chunks.html_content:
You can get help from staff where you’re being held in custody and supporters outside.

Ask the Offender Management Unit in your prison for the name and number of the case manager handling your case.

Your family and friends can also get support.

You can get help from:

  • your solicitor
  • your prisoner offender supervisor or case administrator
  • prison or custodial staff

heading_context: Apply for parole if you're a young offender
Get help from supporters outside
chunks.html_content:
You can ask the following organisations for help:

  • Prisoners Advice Service
  • Howard League
  • Prison Reform Trust

You can also contact the Parole Board for help and advice.

heading_context: Apply for parole if you're a young offender
Your case file
chunks.html_content:
1. Fill in the parole application form - you’ll get this from staff where you’re being held 6 months before the first date you could be allowed to be released, otherwise known as your ‘parole eligibility date’.

  2. Include why you think you should be released and any other information you think is relevant - this will be part of your case file.

  3. Go to a hearing, sometimes known as an oral hearing, if the Parole Board decides it cannot release you based on your case file.

Staff in your unit or on your wing will put together a file about your case of documents about:

  • your offence and any previous convictions
  • your behaviour in prison
  • your plans after you’re released
  • anything else that might help the Parole Board make their decision

Include your own views about why you should be released.

A victim’s personal statement might also be in your case file. It will include how the victim feels about you being released.

heading_context: Apply for parole if you're a young offender
Attend a hearing
chunks.html_content:
You’ll automatically get a hearing if you’re under 18 years old and the Parole Board decides it cannot release you just on the papers in your case file.

Find out what happens at a hearing.

heading_context: Apply for parole if you're a young offender
If you get parole
chunks.html_content:
You’ll get a letter telling you what the Parole Board have decided and why. You’ll get this a few days after a decision is made on your case.

It can take up to 6 months for the Parole Board to meet and make a decision on your case.

You’ll be released on the first date you’re allowed to get parole or as soon as possible, and kept under supervision, known as being ‘on licence’ or probation.

You can get help and financial support once you leave prison.

If you do not get parole
chunks.html_content: Your case will be sent back to the Parole Board at regular intervals if you do not get parole.
